@jamadden what you show is correct POSIX locale semantics: LC_CTYPE overrides LANG (and LC_ALL overrides LC_CTYPE).  LC_CTYPE=C implies US-ASCII as the locale encoding.

Python 3.7 [decided to ignore locale settings and use UTF-8 when the locale is set to C/POSIX](https://docs.python.org/3/whatsnew/3.7.html#whatsnew37-pep538), but your PyPy3 is a 3.6.

So far it looks to me that this tox.ini hack is a workaround for someone's broken local environment, and doesn't really need to be there?  Or, at least, it has no reason to be PyPy-specific, since CPython < 3.7 will also use US-ASCII in these circumstances?

This can be greatly simplified.

`if (viewSelectedTime.endStep === null) {
          viewSelectedTime.startStep = getClosestStep(
            viewSelectedTime.startStep,
            steps
          );
        }`

getClosestStep is like getClosestNonSelectedStep except if the selected step exists it just return it.

`export function getClosestStep(selectedStep: number, steps: number[]): number {
  let minDistance = Infinity;
  let closestStep = null;
  for (const step of steps) {
    const distance = Math.abs(selectedStep - step);
    if (distance < minDistance) {
      minDistance = distance;
      closestStep = step;
    }
  }

  return closestStep || selectedStep;
}`

Then you can get rid of the closestNonSelectedStep$ variable entirely and both of those utility functions.

Let me know what you think.

